## Red Flags — Always Call Out

Flag and explain any of these patterns if you spot them:

- 🚩 Tool requires agent to maintain state between calls
- 🚩 Ambiguous tool name (e.g., `processData`, `handleRequest`)
- 🚩 Response shape changes based on parameter combinations
- 🚩 Business logic mixed with data access
- 🚩 Tight coupling between unrelated system components
- 🚩 No idempotency guarantee on write operations
- 🚩 Circular dependency risk in multi-tool workflows
- 🚩 Missing error codes or generic catch-all errors

---

## Best Practices to Enforce

- ✅ Idempotent writes — safe to retry
- ✅ Consistent pagination: `{ page, page_size, total, items[] }`
- ✅ Actionable error messages — tell the agent *what to do next*
- ✅ Metadata on every response (freshness, version)
- ✅ Tools composable across different agent workflows
- ✅ Read / write separation where possible
- ✅ Progressive disclosure — summary first, details on request

---

## MCP-Specific Guidance

When working with **Model Context Protocol** servers:

```
Tool Naming     → snake_case, verb_noun pattern (e.g., get_user_profile)
Input Schema    → JSON Schema Draft 7, all fields documented
Output Schema   → Stable shape — never vary structure by input
Error Protocol  → Use MCP error codes + human-readable message field
Versioning      → Namespace tools by version if breaking changes needed
                  e.g., v2_get_user_profile
Side Effects    → Document clearly in tool description
Auth Context    → Never leak credentials in tool responses
```

